  "eventMetadata": {
    "context_description": "Canada enters its 2026 FIFA World Cup opener against Bosnia-Herzegovina as slight favorites at BMO Field in Toronto, buoyed by home-soil advantage and recent unbeaten form in friendlies. However, key absences including centre-back Mo\u00efse Bombito and uncertainty over star winger Alphonso Davies due to a hamstring issue temper expectations for a dominant performance. Bosnia, who qualified via playoff victory over Italy, field an experienced squad led by Edin Dzeko alongside emerging talents, positioning them as resilient underdogs capable of exploiting defensive vulnerabilities. The closely contested implied probabilities reflect a matchup where Canada's home support and preparation edge compete against Bosnia's battle-tested mentality and the inherent unpredictability of World Cup group-stage football.",
